00:16:31,720 --> 00:16:36,920
was initially deemed to be much higher. It was only once we appreciated how prevalent it was

199
00:16:36,920 --> 00:16:43,160
that the case fatality rate came so far down. I believe in the end it's less than 0.1% correct?

200
00:16:43,160 --> 00:16:44,040
Yes, yeah, definitely.

201
00:16:44,680 --> 00:16:49,400
What is your real assessment now? And again, you can only be speculating at this point,

202
00:16:49,400 --> 00:16:55,320
I understand, but what do you think is the true case fatality rate of SARS-CoV-2 specifically?

203
00:16:56,040 --> 00:17:01,000
And if you want to answer that, by the way, in terms of I think that the CFR is going to be this

204
00:17:01,000 --> 00:17:05,480
for people over 60 and this for people under 60, and it blends out to this, I mean, answer it any

205
00:17:05,480 --> 00:17:10,600
way you see fit. So the CFR has been really hard to calculate because we have a severity bias

206
00:17:10,600 --> 00:17:15,400
because testing has been so heterogeneous around countries. So what I do is try to look at a place

207
00:17:15,400 --> 00:17:20,360
that's tested extensively and use that as kind of a barometer. And right now, it used to be South

208
00:17:20,360 --> 00:17:24,840
Korea that tested, and now it seems to be Germany is doing the best testing. And you're also looking

209
00:17:24,840 --> 00:17:28,440
at modeling studies. So some of the modeling studies from Imperial College put the case fatality

210
00:17:28,440 --> 00:17:34,200
ratio at 0.66%. Germany looks like it's at a 0.3 something percent.

211
00:17:34,200 --> 00:17:36,920
Yeah, I think 0.37 this morning, yeah.

212
00:17:36,920 --> 00:17:41,640
Yeah, doing antibody testing to try and understand. So I do think it's probably in that range,

213
00:17:41,640 --> 00:17:48,040
probably in the 0.3 to 0.66. I say that with some confidence, but it may drift lower or higher,

214
00:17:48,040 --> 00:17:51,880
depending upon how much severity bias is in the samples. And it's very hard. We probably won't

215
00:17:51,880 --> 00:17:57,080
truly know until we do retrospective studies looking at antibodies to understand how prevalent

216
00:17:57,080 --> 00:18:01,000
it is. And there's differences amongst that because that's an average number. If you're above

217
00:18:01,000 --> 00:18:06,360
80, your case fatality ratio may be as high as 15%. If you're eight years old, your case fatality

218
00:18:06,360 --> 00:18:10,680
ratio may be 0%. So I think it's important to remember that these are average numbers, and it's

219
00:18:10,680 --> 00:18:15,640
not every person carries that risk. Some people will have much, much higher risks, and some people

220
00:18:15,640 --> 00:18:19,880
will have lower risks. And I think that's sometimes lost in nuance when you try to come up with one

221
00:18:19,880 --> 00:18:20,760
number.

222
00:18:20,760 --> 00:18:26,440
Absolutely, yeah. Blending that is, there's lots of glib examples of how you can drown in an average

223
00:18:26,440 --> 00:18:31,640
of three inches of water, of course, if you're walking across a river that has vacillating depth.

224
00:18:31,640 --> 00:18:36,440
Because you're, again, kind of a veteran of this, what do you think was sort of the

225
00:18:38,040 --> 00:18:44,440
overslash, underdoing of some of the predictions that came out in the sort of Gen 1 models that

226
00:18:44,440 --> 00:18:49,240
showed up in sort of February where they were saying, look, this is something that is going to

227
00:18:49,240 --> 00:18:56,040
infect 200 million Americans. It's going to kill two to four million Americans. Do you think that

228
00:18:56,120 --> 00:19:02,760
that type of modeling historically has ever shown to be accurate? Or do you think that, yes,

229
00:19:02,760 --> 00:19:07,800
that was accurate, and it's the measures that are in place that are going to hopefully prevent that

230
00:19:07,800 --> 00:19:14,280
from happening? Because it seems less likely now that we're heading in the direction of those types

231
00:19:14,280 --> 00:19:19,240
of doomsday scenarios. But again, it's hard to know how much of that is in response to the

232
00:19:19,240 --> 00:19:25,480
measures that have been enacted versus predictions that were predicated on poorly understood things,

233
00:19:25,480 --> 00:19:31,640
including what the R0 was. I think that models you have to realize have assumptions built into

234
00:19:31,640 --> 00:19:35,640
them. And you have to look at those assumptions, because just a small difference in the assumption

235
00:19:35,640 --> 00:19:39,480
can lead to a big change on the end of it. And what I would think, at least from my

236
00:19:40,040 --> 00:19:45,720
understanding of many of the models, is that the hospitalization rate was probably overstated.

237
00:19:45,720 --> 00:19:50,520
Because we know, for example, that the diagnosis that we're talking about in any given city or town

238
00:19:50,520 --> 00:19:54,760
are likely understated by a factor of at least maybe 10. And I can say that from my own practice

239
00:19:54,840 --> 00:19:58,280
when I order the test and don't order the test. There's many patients, I think, have the disease

240
00:19:58,280 --> 00:20:03,560
and I don't order the test. So there clearly is a severity bias in who gets tested. And then I

241
00:20:03,560 --> 00:20:08,760
think you see this idea of 15% to 20% getting admitted to the hospital. I think that that

242
00:20:08,760 --> 00:20:13,880
doesn't necessarily mean everybody of the people that get infected, maybe that's 40% of the

243
00:20:13,880 --> 00:20:20,440
population over time, that 15% to 20% of those individuals get admitted. It's more like, of the

244
00:20:20,440 --> 00:20:24,920
40% of the population that get infected, the ones who go to an emergency department,

245
00:20:24,920 --> 00:20:30,360
15 to 20% get admitted. And maybe the real hospitalization rate is 5%. If you look at,

246
00:20:30,360 --> 00:20:34,120
for example, Westchester County's data, which I haven't looked at lately, but the last time I

247
00:20:34,120 --> 00:20:38,520
looked, they did a lot of heavy testing in that part of New York State, because they had that

248
00:20:38,520 --> 00:20:43,880
outbreak in New Rochelle. And their hospitalization rate was around 5%, a little bit less than 5% the

249
00:20:43,880 --> 00:20:49,640
last time I calculated it. And that changes, that gives you a major change from going down from 20%

250
00:20:49,720 --> 00:20:54,680
to 5% in terms of what your ventilator needs are, what your ICU bed capacity needs are,

251
00:20:54,680 --> 00:20:59,960
and what the case fatality ratio is going to be if you look at what the hospitalization rate is.

252
00:20:59,960 --> 00:21:04,920
And I think that that's at least one of my criticisms of some of the models, the hospitalization

253
00:21:04,920 --> 00:21:10,280
rate was set too high. And if they were taking too big of a fraction using the wrong denominator,

254
00:21:10,280 --> 00:21:14,680
I think, to come up with what their case fatality ratios are, what their ICU bed needs would be,

255
00:21:14,680 --> 00:21:18,520
and what their mechanical ventilation needs would be. And that happens because models have lots of

256
00:21:18,600 --> 00:21:22,760
assumption in them. And they should be used as tools. They're not ironclad. And I think that

257
00:21:22,760 --> 00:21:27,560
sometimes that gets lost in the press reporting of them, they get looked at as if they are the truth,

258
00:21:27,560 --> 00:21:31,960
and they need to be revised. And when you have real data from real hospitals and real people,

259
00:21:31,960 --> 00:21:36,360
it should supplant what you're using with a model. So if your model is not matching reality,

260
00:21:36,360 --> 00:21:39,480
then I think you need to either change the assumptions on the model or actually look at

261
00:21:39,480 --> 00:21:44,520
reality. These are tools and all models are going to be wrong. Some of them are going to be useful,

262
00:21:44,520 --> 00:21:48,680
and some of them are not going to be useful. I agree. I think it's unfortunately the press

263
00:21:48,680 --> 00:21:54,120
sometimes views corrections of models as a sign of weakness as opposed to a necessary part of the

264
00:21:54,120 --> 00:21:59,000
evolution of utilizing the tool as you described it. We've talked a little bit about this being a

265
00:21:59,000 --> 00:22:06,360
dress rehearsal for what is coming unquestionably at some point, very likely in our lifetimes,

266
00:22:06,360 --> 00:22:12,120
which is another pandemic, another virus, and potentially one that could be much more devastating.

267
00:22:12,120 --> 00:22:20,520
You used an example of viruses that are typically transmitted only from animals to humans that can

268
00:22:20,520 --> 00:22:25,640
potentially be much more catastrophic. But if those viruses ever figure out how to go human to human,

269
00:22:25,640 --> 00:22:34,760
they spread much more. What is your view on the role of local versus central government in

270
00:22:35,400 --> 00:22:41,800
dealing with that? Can't imagine there isn't a role for both, but I feel personally very confused

271
00:22:41,800 --> 00:22:46,520
when I try to sometimes play the game. If I was czar for a day, what would I do different? But the

272
00:22:46,520 --> 00:22:50,440
reality of it is it's easy to play armchair quarterback. I'm not really sure I know

273
00:22:50,440 --> 00:22:55,720
what the federal government should be doing in this situation versus the state governments and

274
00:22:55,720 --> 00:23:00,360
local governments. This is something that's pretty unique to the United States because we have a system

275
00:23:00,360 --> 00:23:05,560
of a federal government with states and locals having most of the power, especially true in

276
00:23:05,560 --> 00:23:09,400
public health because most of the public health powers are vested at the local and state level.

277
00:23:09,400 --> 00:23:14,200
The federal government is more of a coordinator. Even the CDC can't actually get involved in

278
00:23:14,200 --> 00:23:19,480
something unless they're asked by a state. You will often see differences and heterogeneity

279
00:23:19,480 --> 00:23:24,360
between recommendations from maybe one county to the next and definitely from one state to the next.

280
00:23:24,360 --> 00:23:30,040
Sometimes that can be confusing. I do think that I'm generally supportive of local health departments

281
00:23:30,040 --> 00:23:33,320
being the ones running it because they actually know their community, they know their capacities,

282
00:23:33,320 --> 00:23:38,840
they know where their gaps are, and they're able to really be on the ground with the people and

283
00:23:38,840 --> 00:23:43,960
able to do great things when it comes to stopping an outbreak. But often what we find is local health

284
00:23:43,960 --> 00:23:48,040
departments aren't appropriately resourced. You've got one person doing four different roles in a

285
00:23:48,040 --> 00:23:52,440
small town's health department, and that can be very constraining. What you need to really do is

286
00:23:52,440 --> 00:23:56,920
have those local health departments actually operating the way that they should be and thought

287
00:23:56,920 --> 00:24:03,640
of as part of the whole pandemic response apparatus, whereas many people think of just the CDC, the NIH,

288
00:24:03,640 --> 00:24:06,840
and parts of the Health and Human Services Department as the main pandemic apparatus.

289
00:24:06,920 --> 00:24:12,760
It's actually the local health departments that do all that case finding and isolation and talk to

290
00:24:12,760 --> 00:24:16,920
the public and deal with hospital capacity levels. It's the local health department, so I can't

291
00:24:16,920 --> 00:24:21,960
overstate how important local health departments are. I do think that that system works well,

292
00:24:21,960 --> 00:24:26,920
but you do need to have federal leadership to guide the nation as a whole on what to expect

293
00:24:26,920 --> 00:24:31,400
and what's going on. I think that's sort of been missing a lot during this outbreak compared to

294
00:24:31,400 --> 00:24:36,040
other outbreaks. Because of that, you've seen governors at state health departments take on

295
00:24:36,040 --> 00:24:40,120
roles that they usually haven't taken, where they've deferred much more to federal experts,

296
00:24:40,120 --> 00:24:45,880
not the powers, but the guidance and looking to them to set the tone. I think now we're finding

297
00:24:45,880 --> 00:24:49,960
governors basically stepping into that role for the most part, and even mayors in some places.

298
00:24:50,600 --> 00:24:53,640
I think that can be confusing to a member of the general public because they don't know who to

299
00:24:53,640 --> 00:24:57,400
believe, especially if there's conflicting information. You have a press that's constantly

300
00:24:57,400 --> 00:25:00,760
trying to pit one governor against another governor or against the federal government,

301
00:25:00,760 --> 00:25:04,760
and that makes it much harder. I do think that when the process works well with local,

302
00:25:04,760 --> 00:25:09,320
state, and federal government all in step, all doing the appropriate roles, I do think it works

303
00:25:09,320 --> 00:25:14,440
pretty well. You have a locally managed, federally coordinated response, which I think is the best

304
00:25:14,440 --> 00:25:20,040
way to think about how it would be ideally done. Is it safe to say that testing is really something

305
00:25:20,040 --> 00:25:24,920
that like if you go back in time and maybe change one thing, if we're sitting here and it's January

306
00:25:24,920 --> 00:25:30,520
12th and we now have the sequence of this virus, would that have potentially been one of the more

307
00:25:30,520 --> 00:25:35,080
important things for the federal government, for that centralized piece of government to have put

308
00:25:35,080 --> 00:25:40,120
in place? The CDC could have said, look, we're going to make this the highest priority because

309
00:25:40,120 --> 00:25:43,800
it strikes me as that's something very difficult to be done in a decentralized manner.

310
00:25:44,760 --> 00:25:49,800
What happened was the CDC put out guidance on who should be tested, which basically was taken as

311
00:25:49,800 --> 00:25:54,120
gospel by the state health departments. That included only people that had traveled to China

312
00:25:54,120 --> 00:26:00,280
in the last 14 days, as well as someone who had to have lower respiratory tract symptoms. You

313
00:26:00,280 --> 00:26:04,600
couldn't have just had a sore throat. You had to have evidence that maybe you had pneumonia to be

314
00:26:04,600 --> 00:26:08,760
tested. So we weren't testing mild cases and we weren't testing people that hadn't come to China.

315
00:26:08,760 --> 00:26:12,440
That was a federal decision. And I think that could have been done better and allowed much more

316
00:26:12,440 --> 00:26:17,000
latitude. Because you can remember that first case in California that didn't have traveled to China,

317
00:26:17,000 --> 00:26:22,360
they, the hospital had to actually fight to get that test run. And there were many cases like that

318
00:26:22,360 --> 00:26:27,320
all over the country. And if you look at New York's epidemiology, their introduction of the virus

319
00:26:27,320 --> 00:26:32,680
was not from China, it was from Europe. And that slips through the type of testing algorithm. So

